		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id720171c682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>8:24.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Comparable sales</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Evidence of comparable sales of similar property is relevant to prove market value. <eos/>
						<bos/>Although not restricted to real estate, most cases considering comparable sales occur in this area.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7972ce7074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Generally, a voluntary sale of similar property in the vicinity, not too far removed in point of time, will be admissible to prove market value of the tract in question.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7972ce7174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Data concerning comparable sales is the best test of market value in condemnation cases.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7972ce7274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>A lay or expert witness may offer direct evidence of the comparable sale.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7972f58074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>An expert witness may testify about comparable sales based upon research done by his staff.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7972f58174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] The comparable sale must have been a voluntary sale.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Sales of other property to a condemnor are not admissible.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7972f58274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The other sale offered as evidence must have been a completed sale.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7972f58374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<?page no="262"?>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The determination of whether the sale offered in evidence is in fact a comparable sale lies within the discretion of the trial judge.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I79731c9074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] It is error to exclude a comparable sale and error to admit an incomparable sale. <eos/>
						<bos/>Moreover, the differences in geographical locations and dates of comparable sales go to the weight, rather than the admissibility, of the comparable sales.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I79731c9174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017149" w-serial-number="1965126873" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="If3641c8274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>State Highway Dept. v. Rutland</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I79731c9274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals held that a tract of similar farmland one-half mile away from the property in question was sufficiently comparable, even though the soil was different, and excluding evidence of the value of that land when sold a year before was erroneous.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Comparable sales evidence is admissible in criminal cases to prove the value of stolen or destroyed property. <eos/>
						<bos/>The value of the property may be shown by (1) <begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>“the cost of an item, as long as it is coupled with other evidence of its condition before and after the damage,”<end.quote refid="QT_0003"/> (2) evidence of the cost of repair, or (3) testimony from a lay witness as long as the witness states <begin.quote ID="QT_0004"/>“the facts on which she bases her opinion or otherwise shows she had the opportunity to form a correct opinion.”<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<end.quote refid="QT_0004"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I79731c9374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference>] The value of property in criminal cases must be shown beyond a reasonable doubt.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I79731c9474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">12</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
